Economic Growth & Corporate Earnings Cycle: The stock market is forward-looking, often rising during economic expansions when corporate earnings are growing, and faltering when a recession looms (earnings decline). The business cycle (expansion -> peak -> recession -> trough -> expansion) is a cornerstone of equity pricing. During the early and mid-expansion phases, stocks tend to do well as revenues and profits climb. In late-cycle expansions, if growth overheats or inflation picks up, stocks can become choppier, anticipating a downturn. Once a recession hits, stocks usually enter a bear market (a decline >20%), often bottoming before the recession officially ends in anticipation of recovery. For instance, in the 2008–2009 Global Financial Crisis, SPX peaked in late 2007 when the economy was still seemingly fine, then plunged throughout 2008 as the recession unfolded, bottoming in March 2009 even though the recession didn’t end until later that year. The subsequent expansion (2009-2019) saw a long bull market. Similarly, the 2020 COVID recession caused one of the fastest bear market drops (SPX fell ~34% in a month) followed by a steep recovery as stimulus and reopening drove a new expansion. Traders should watch economic indicators (GDP, unemployment, PMIs, consumer spending) as well as corporate earnings reports and guidance. If earnings are in an upswing (companies beating expectations, raising forecasts), that’s bullish for stocks. If earnings are contracting or many warnings are issued, it’s bearish. In a confluence score, one could incorporate an earnings trend factor (e.g. positive earnings revisions breadth = +1, negative revisions = –1). Often, the stock market tops out about 6–9 months before earnings peak and bottoms ~6 months before earnings trough – this is the earnings cycle lead-lag. Recognizing those inflection points is key.
